Introduction
As software applications grow, maintaining the codebase becomes increasingly challenging. Features evolve, business requirements change, and new developers join the team. Without proper design principles, even a well-written application can become difficult to extend and maintain.
This is where the SOLID principles come into play.
SOLID is a set of five object-oriented design principles introduced by Robert C. Martin (Uncle Bob). These principles help developers write code that is maintainable, scalable, loosely coupled, reusable, and easy to test.
Whether you’re preparing for Java interviews, building Spring Boot applications, or working on enterprise software, understanding SOLID is essential.
The acronym SOLID stands for:

• S — Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)

• O — Open/Closed Principle (OCP)

• L — Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP)

• I — Interface Segregation Principle (ISP)

• D — Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP)
Let’s explore each principle in depth.
1. Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)
Definition
A class should have only one reason to change.
In simple terms, every class should focus on one responsibility or one job.
If a class handles multiple responsibilities, changes in one responsibility may unintentionally affect the others, making the code difficult to maintain.
Bad Example
Imagine a class responsible for user registration.
public class UserService {
public void registerUser(User user) {
System.out.println("Registering user...");
}
public void saveToDatabase(User user) {
System.out.println("Saving user to database...");
}
public void sendWelcomeEmail(User user) {
System.out.println("Sending welcome email...");
}
}What’s wrong?
This class is responsible for:

• User registration

• Database operations

• Email notifications
If the email service changes, this class changes.
If the database changes, this class changes.
If registration logic changes, this class changes.
It has multiple reasons to change, violating SRP.
Good Example
Separate responsibilities into different classes.
public class UserService {
public void registerUser(User user) {
System.out.println("User registered successfully.");
}
} public class UserRepository {
public void save(User user) {
System.out.println("User saved in database.");
}
}
public class EmailService {
public void sendWelcomeEmail(User user) {
System.out.println("Welcome email sent.");
}
}
Now each class has one responsibility.
Benefits

• Easier maintenance

• Better readability

• Easier testing

• Lower coupling

• Better code organization
2. Open/Closed Principle (OCP)
Definition
Software entities should be open for extension but closed for modification
Instead of modifying existing code whenever a new feature is required, we should extend the application by adding new classes.
Bad Example
public class PaymentService {
public void processPayment(String paymentType) {
if(paymentType.equals("CARD")) {
System.out.println("Card payment");
}
else if(paymentType.equals("UPI")) {
System.out.println("UPI payment");
}
}
}Suppose tomorrow you add PayPal or Net Banking.
You’ll have to modify this class again.
This violates OCP.
Good Example
Create an abstraction.
public interface Payment {
void pay();
}Implementation for Card Payment:
public class CardPayment implements Payment {
@Override
public void pay() {
System.out.println("Processing Card Payment");
}
}Implementation for UPI:
public class UpiPayment implements Payment {
@Override
public void pay() {
System.out.println("Processing UPI Payment");
}
}Payment Service:
public class PaymentService {
public void processPayment(Payment payment) {
payment.pay();
}
}Adding a new payment method becomes easy.
public class PayPalPayment implements Payment {
@Override
public void pay() {
System.out.println("Processing PayPal Payment");
}
}No existing code needs modification.
Benefits

• Easier feature addition

• Lower risk of breaking existing functionality

• Better scalability
3. Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP)
Definition
Subclasses should be substitutable for their base classes without altering the correctness of the program.
If class B extends class A, then object B should work anywhere object A is expected.
Inheritance should preserve behavior, not break it.
Bad Example
class Bird {
public void fly() {
System.out.println("Bird is flying");
}
}class Sparrow extends Bird {
@Override
public void fly() {
System.out.println("Sparrow is flying");
}
}
class Penguin extends Bird {
@Override
public void fly() {
throw new UnsupportedOperationException("Penguins cannot fly");
}
}
Client code:
public void makeBirdFly(Bird bird) {
bird.fly();
}This works for Sparrow but crashes for Penguin.
The child class changed the expected behavior.
This violates LSP.
Better Design
Separate flying behavior.
interface Bird {
}interface FlyingBird {
void fly();
}
class Sparrow implements Bird, FlyingBird {
@Override
public void fly() {
System.out.println("Sparrow flying");
}
}
class Penguin implements Bird {
public void swim() {
System.out.println("Penguin swimming");
}
}
Now only birds capable of flying implement FlyingBird.
Benefits

• Correct inheritance hierarchy

• Reliable polymorphism

• Fewer runtime surprises
4. Interface Segregation Principle (ISP)
Definition
Clients should not be forced to depend upon interfaces they do not use.
Instead of one large interface, create multiple small and focused interfaces.
Bad Example
interface Worker {
void work();
void eat();
void sleep();
}Human implementation:
class HumanWorker implements Worker {
public void work() {
System.out.println("Working...");
}
public void eat() {
System.out.println("Eating...");
}
public void sleep() {
System.out.println("Sleeping...");
}
}Robot implementation:
class RobotWorker implements Worker {
public void work() {
System.out.println("Working...");
}
public void eat() {
// Not applicable
}
public void sleep() {
// Not applicable
}
}Robot is forced to implement unnecessary methods.
This violates ISP.
Better Design
Split the interface.
interface Workable {
void work();
}interface Eatable {
void eat();
}
interface Sleepable {
void sleep();
}
Human:
class HumanWorker implements Workable, Eatable, Sleepable {
public void work() {}
public void eat() {}
public void sleep() {}
}Robot:
class RobotWorker implements Workable {
public void work() {}
}Now every class implements only the behavior it actually needs.
Benefits

• Cleaner interfaces

• Less unnecessary code

• Easier maintenance

• Better flexibility
5. Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP)
Definition
High-level modules should not depend on low-level modules. Both should depend on abstractions.
Business logic should depend on interfaces rather than concrete implementations.
Bad Example
class MySQLDatabase {
public void connect() {
System.out.println("Connected to MySQL");
}
}class UserService {
private MySQLDatabase database = new MySQLDatabase();
public void saveUser() {
database.connect();
}
}
Problems:

• Tight coupling

• Difficult to replace database

• Difficult to test
Better Design
Create an abstraction.
interface Database {
void connect();
}Implementation:
class MySQLDatabase implements Database {
@Override
public void connect() {
System.out.println("Connected to MySQL");
}
}class PostgreSQLDatabase implements Database {
@Override
public void connect() {
System.out.println("Connected to PostgreSQL");
}
}
Inject the dependency.
class UserService {
private final Database database; public UserService(Database database) {
this.database = database;
}
public void saveUser() {
database.connect();
System.out.println("User saved");
}
}
Usage:
Database db = new MySQLDatabase();UserService service = new UserService(db);
service.saveUser();
If tomorrow you switch to PostgreSQL:
Database db = new PostgreSQLDatabase();No changes are required in UserService.
Benefits

• Loose coupling

• Better unit testing

• Easier maintenance

• Easier implementation swapping

• Core principle behind Spring Dependency Injection
SOLID in Spring Boot
Spring Boot naturally encourages SOLID principles:

• SRP → Separate Controllers, Services, and Repositories

• OCP → Extend functionality using interfaces and new implementations

• LSP → Different service implementations can replace each other without affecting clients

• ISP → Create focused service interfaces rather than large, generic ones

• DIP → Dependency Injection through constructor injection and the IoC container
For example:
@Service
public class UserService { private final UserRepository repository;
public UserService(UserRepository repository) {
this.repository = repository;
}
}
Spring injects the required implementation automatically, promoting loose coupling.
