Conclusion
SOLID principles are not rigid rules but proven design guidelines that help developers build robust and maintainable software. By following these principles, applications become easier to extend, easier to test, and less prone to unexpected bugs caused by tightly coupled code.
Modern frameworks like Spring Boot are built around these ideas, especially Dependency Inversion through Dependency Injection and Single Responsibility through layered architecture.
Mastering SOLID will not only improve the quality of your code but also strengthen your understanding of object-oriented design, making you a better software engineer and preparing you for real-world development as well as technical interviews.
The next time you design a class or interface, ask yourself: Is this class doing too much? Can I extend this without modifying existing code? Am I depending on abstractions instead of concrete implementations? These questions are at the heart of writing clean, maintainable software.
